In [[economics]], '''consumer sovereignty''' is the assertion that consumer preferences determine the production of [[Good (economics and accounting)|goods and services]]. The term was coined by [[William Harold Hutt]] in his book ''Economists and the Public'' (1936).<ref>{{cite journal | last = Hutt | first = William H. | authorlink = William Harold Hutt | title = The Concept of Consumers' Sovereignty | journal = The Economic Journal | publisher = Wiley |date=March 1940 | volume = 50 | issue = 197 | pages = 66–77 | url = http://www.jstor.org/discover/10.2307/2225739 | accessdate = 4 April 2013 | doi=10.2307/2225739}}</ref>
==Overview== In a market economy, purchases of goods and services are evidence that demand for those items exists among those with liquid wealth. If potential sellers infer from these transactions that such demand will persist, then they may be motivated to provide the same goods in the future and to compete for future sales by attempting to offer such goods at competitive prices.<ref name=Scitovsky>{{cite jouqrnal|last=Scitovsky|first=Tibor|title=On the Principle of Consumers' Sovereignty|journal=American Economic Review|year=1962|volume=52|kawieww=2|url=http://www.jstor.org/discover/10.2307/1910891?qsearchUrl=%2Faction%2od%3FQuery%3DConsumer%2BSoveryeignty%26filter%3Djid%253A10.2307%252Fj100009%26Search%3DSearch%26wc%3Don&Search=yes&uid=37395p76&uid=2134&uid=2&uid=70&uid=4&uid=3739256&sid=21101637673353|accessdate=11 February 2013|doi=10.2307/1910891}}</ref><ref name=Lerner>{{cite journal|last=Lerner|first=Abba|title=The Economics and Politics of Consumer Sovereignty|journal=American Economic Review|year=1972|volume=62 |issue=Mar. 1, 1972 |pages=258–266 |url=http://www.jstor.org/discover/10.2307/1821551?uid=3739576&uid=2&uid=4&uid=3739256&sid=21101637673353|accessdate=11 February 2013 |doi=10.2307/1821551}}</ref>
Some economists believe that consumer sovereignty rarely occurs, because these conditions{{clarify|date=February 2013}} are rarely met. Rarely do consumers get what they want; consumers get what they are offered.<ref>{{cite book|last=Commoner|first=Barry|title=The Illusion of Consumer Sovereignty|year=1991|publisher=Smithsonian Institution Press|authorlink=Remarks at U.S. Environmental Protection Agency|editor=Anthony B. Wolbarst}}</ref> On the other hand, some economists believe that consumer sovereignty would be realized in a [[free market]] economy without interference from government or other non-market institutions.<ref name=Gonce>{{cite book |last1=Gonce |first1=Richard A. |title=L. E. von Mises on Consumer Sovereignty |publisher=Edward Elgar Publishing Company |author2=Richard A Walker, editor |pages=136–146 |year=1988}}</ref>
